🔐 What is SSH?

SSH (Secure Shell) is a protocol used to connect securely to a remote computer/server over a network.

🧠 Simple Definition (Interview Style)

👉 SSH is a secure way to access and control a remote server using the command line.

🏠 Easy Example

Think of SSH like a remote control for your server:

Your laptop = Remote
Server = TV
SSH = Secure connection between them

You can sit at home and control a server anywhere in the world.

⚙️ How SSH works
It connects using:
IP address
Username
Password or Key (recommended)
Default port = 22

Example command:

ssh ubuntu@192.168.1.10
🔑 Why SSH is used?
Secure login 🔒 (encrypted connection)
Remote server control 🖥️
File transfer (using SCP/SFTP)
Manage cloud servers (like AWS EC2)
🚀 Real Example

When you create a server in AWS:

You connect using SSH:
ssh -i key.pem ubuntu@your-public-ip
⚠️ Important
SSH is encrypted (safe)
Never share your private key (.pem file)
🎯 Short Answer (for interview)

👉 “SSH is a secure protocol used to remotely access and manage servers over a network.”
